# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buryat-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] The **A-Hmao** (or **Ahmao**) **language**, also known as **Large Flowery Miao** (pinyin: *Dà Huā Miáo*), **Hua Miao**, or **Northeast Yunnan** (Chinese: 苗语滇东北方言; pinyin: *Miáoyǔ Diàndōngběi fāngyán*), is a Hmongic language spoken in China.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] It is the language for which the Pollard script was designed and displays extensive tone sandhi.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] A-Hmao is a branch of the West Hmongic languages, also known as Chuanqiandian Miao (Chinese: 川黔滇苗; lit.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] 'Sichuan–Guizhou–Yunnan Miao') and Western Miao.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] West Hmongic Languages are a major branch of the Hmongic languages of China and Southeast Asia.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] A-Hmao is a language spoken in the northeast of Yunnan Province and in the west of Guizhou Province, particularly in Zhaotong, Kunming, Qujing, Chuxiong Yi autonomous prefecture, Weining Yi, Hui, and Miao autonomous county, Hezhang county, Liupanshui, and Ziyun Miao and Buyi autonomous county.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] The standard dialect is that of Shimenkan (石门坎), Weining County (威宁县).
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] The fourth, sixth, and eighth tones of A-Hmao, in the eastern region, are broken up partially or entirely into two categories based on the eight tones.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] At most, there can be up to eleven tones.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Essentially, nouns and quantifiers are part of the first category, and they are higher in pitch.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Other word classes are part of the second category, and they are lower in pitch.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] A-Hmao language displays extensive tone sandhi.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Similar to other branches of the West Hmongic languages, the tone sandhi happens on the second syllable when the first syllable of a disyllabic word is a level tone (first and second tone).
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] The morphology of the three branches of the Hmong language are very similar.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] The following examples are from Central Miao.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] A-Hmao is similar to Hmong, which is an isolating language where most morphemes are monosyllables, resulting in verbs not being overtly inflected.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Tense, aspect, mood, person, number, gender, and case are indicated lexically.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] (There is a small number of multisyllable single-morpheme words in the Hmong language.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Verb morpheme compound with verb morpheme.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Adjective morpheme compound with adjective morpheme.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Adjective morpheme modifying noun morpheme.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Adjective morpheme dominating noun morpheme.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Affixes Mostly are prefixes, and commonly used prefixes are *ghab-, diub-, hangd-, gid-, jib-, daib-, bod-, xuk-*, and so on.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] *Hangd-/khangd-* means aspect and direction.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] *Daib-* means person and some kinship terminology.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] One unusual feature of A-Hmao morphology is the existence of inflecting classifiers, i.e., classifiers that change form.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] As with other Hmongic languages, the basic word order of A-Hmao is subject-verb-object.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Within the noun phrase, possessors precede possessed nouns, while relative clauses precede the nouns they modify.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Noun phrases have the form (possessive) + (quantifier) + (classifier) + noun + (adjective) + (demonstrative).
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Question formation in Ahmao does not involve word order change: question words generally remain in situ, rather than appearing in sentence-initial position, and pseudo-clefting is also usually used in questions.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] A-Hmao exhibits the grammatical patterns as in the table below.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] A-Hmao does not have an indigenous writing system.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] At the beginning of the 20th century, missionary Samuel Pollard invented the Pollard script, which was based on the decorative symbols on their clothing.
[src:buryat-language/a-hmao-language] Before the introduction of the Pollard script, the A-Hmao people recorded their history through their ancient songs and weaved the history of their memories on their clothes, forming the history for A-Hmao.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Abaza is spoken by approximately 35,000 people in Russia, where it is written in a Cyrillic alphabet, as well as another 10,000 in Turkey, where the Latin script is used.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] It consists of two dialects, the Ashkherewa dialect and the T'ap'anta dialect, which is the literary standard.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The language also consists of five subdialects known as Psyzh-Krasnovostok, Abazakt, Apsua, Kubin-Elburgan and Kuvin.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Abaza, like its relatives in the family of Northwest Caucasian languages, is a highly agglutinative language.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] For example, the verb in the English sentence "He couldn't make them give it back to her" contains four arguments (a term used in valency grammar): *he*, *them*, *it*, *to her*.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Abaza marks arguments morphologically, and incorporates all four arguments as pronominal prefixes on the verb.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] It has a large consonantal inventory (63 phonemes) coupled with a minimal vowel inventory (two vowels).
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] It is very closely related to Abkhaz, but it preserves a few phonemes which Abkhaz lacks, such as a voiced pharyngeal fricative.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Work on Abaza has been carried out by W.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Allen, Brian O'Herin, and John Colarusso.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Different forms of cultural assimilation contributed to its fall in use in areas of Russia, and over time its overall endangerment.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The language can be broken into five different dialects and has several unique grammatical approaches to languages.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was at its peak usage in the mid to late 19th century.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Abaza speakers along the Greater and Lesser Laba, Urup, and Greater and Lesser Zelenchuk rivers are from a wave of migrants in the 17th to 18th centuries who represent the Abaza speakers of today.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The end of the Great Caucasian War in 1864 provided Russia with power and control of the local regions and contributed to the decrease in the popularity of pre-existing local languages prior to the war.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was not a written language until the Latin alphabet was adopted in 1932–1933 to write it.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The Cyrillic script was later utilized to write the language in 1938.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] A small amount of books, pamphlets, and a newspaper were published in the Abaza language afterwards.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language is spoken in Russia and Turkey.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Although it is endangered, it is still spoken in several regions in Russia.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] These include Kara-Pago, Kubina, Psyzh, El'burgan, Inzhich-Chukun, Koi-dan, Abaza-Khabl', Malo-Abazinka, Tapanta, Krasnovostochni, Novokuvinski, Starokuvinski, Abazakt and Ap-sua.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The vowels [o, a, u] may have a /j/ in front of it.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e] and [i] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before palatalized consonants, while the vowels [o] and [u] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before labialized consonants.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e], [o], [i], and [u] can also occur as variants of the sequences /aj/, /aw/, /əj/ and /əw/.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Abaza does not have the long low vowel found in Kabardian, preserving it as /aʕ/ or /ʕa/.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, there were attempts to write Abaza with the Arabic script, but none of these attempts took hold.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] In 1932, the first widely used Abaza alphabet was created using the Latin script.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Since 1938, Abaza has been written with the version of the Cyrillic alphabet shown below.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] The digraphs Лӏ and Фӏ are dialectal, and are therefore absent from the literary language and the official alphabet.
[src:buryat-language/abaza-language] Sultan Laguchev, a singer-songwriter famous in Russia, writes and performs songs in the Abaza language, including "Абыгъь гӏважьква" and "БаъапI бара." He has written an additional song in Russian entitled "Мы абазины" ('We are Abazins') about Abazinia.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] In grammar, the **ablative case** (pronounced /ˈæblətɪv/ *AB-lə-tiv*; abbreviated **abl**) is a grammatical case for nouns, pronouns, and adjectives in the grammars of various languages.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] It is used to indicate motion away from something.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] In different languages it can additionally serve various other purposes, *e.g.*, to make comparisons (in Armenian).
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The word "ablative" derives from the Latin *ablatus*, the (suppletive) perfect, passive participle of *auferre* "to carry away".
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative case is found in several language families, such as Indo-European (e.g.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Sanskrit, Latin, Albanian, Armenian, Punjabi), Turkic (e.g.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Turkish, Turkmen, Azerbaijani, Uzbek, Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Tatar), Tungusic (e.g.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Hungarian), and the Dravidian languages.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] There is no ablative case in modern Germanic languages such as German and English.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] There was an ablative case in the early stages of Ancient Greek, but it quickly fell into disuse by the classical period.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative case in Latin (*cāsus ablātīvus*) appears in various grammatical constructions, including following various prepositions, in an ablative absolute clause, and adverbially.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The Latin ablative case was derived from three Proto-Indo-European cases: ablative (from), instrumental (with), and locative (in/at).
[src:buryat-language/ablative] In Ancient Greek, there was an ablative case (ἀφαιρετικὴ πτῶσις *aphairetikē ptōsis*) which was used in the Homeric, pre-Mycenaean, and Mycenean periods.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] It fell into disuse during the classical period and thereafter with some of its functions taken by the genitive and others by the dative.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The genitive case with the prepositions ἀπό *apó* 'away from' and ἐκ/ἐξ *ek/ex* 'out of' is an example.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] German does not have an ablative case but, exceptionally, Latin ablative case-forms were used from the seventeenth to the nineteenth century after some prepositions, for example after *von* in *von dem Nomine*: ablative of the Latin loanword *nomen*.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Grammarians at that time, Justus Georg Schottel, Kaspar von Stieler, Johann Balthasar von Antesperg and Johann Christoph Gottsched, listed an ablative case (as the sixth case after nominative, genitive, dative, accusative and vocative) for German words.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] They considered the dative case after some prepositions to be an ablative, as in *von dem Mann[e]* 'from the man, of the man' and *mit dem Mann[e]* 'with the man', while they considered the dative case after other prepositions or without a preposition, as in *dem Mann[e]*, to be a dative.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative case is found in Albanian; it is the fifth case, *rasa rrjedhore*.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] In Sanskrit, the ablative case is the fifth case (*pañcamī*) and has a similar function to that in Latin.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Sanskrit nouns in the ablative often refer to a subject "out of" which or "from" whom something (an action, an object) has arisen or occurred: *pátram **vṛkṣā́t** pátati* 'the leaf falls **from the tree**'.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] It is also used for nouns in several other senses, as for actions occurring "because of" or "without" a certain noun, indicating distance or direction.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] When it appears with a comparative adjective, (*śreṣṭhatamam* 'the best'), the ablative is used to refer to what the adjective is comparing: 'better than X'.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The modern Armenian ablative has different markers for each main dialect, both originating from Classical Armenian.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The Western Armenian affix -է *-ē* (definite -էն *-ēn*) derives from the classical singular; the Eastern Armenian affix -ից *-ic’* (both indefinite and definite) derives from the classical plural.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] For both dialects, those affixes are singular, with the corresponding plurals being -(ն)երէ(ն) *-(n)erē(n)* and -(ն)երից *-(n)eric’*.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] In Finnish, the ablative case is the sixth of the locative cases with the meaning "from, off, of": *pöytä – pöydältä* "table – off from the table".
[src:buryat-language/ablative] It is an outer locative case, used like the adessive and allative cases, to denote both being on top of something and "being around the place" (as opposed to the inner locative case, the elative, which means "from out of" or "from the inside of").
[src:buryat-language/ablative] With the locative, the receding object was near the other place or object, not inside it.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The Finnish ablative is also used in time expressions to indicate times of something happening (*kymmeneltä* "at ten") as well as with verbs expressing feelings or emotions.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The Finnish ablative has the ending *-lta* or *-ltä*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative case in Estonian is the ninth case and has a similar function to that in Hungarian.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative case in Hungarian is used to describe movement away from, as well as a concept, object, act or event originating from an object, person, location or entity.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] When used to describe movement away from a location, the case may only refer to movement from *the general vicinity* of the location and not from inside of it.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Thus, *a postától jövök* would mean one had been standing *next to* the post office before, not inside the building.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] When the case is used to refer to the origin of a possible act or event, the act/event may be implied while not explicitly stated, such as *Meg foglak védeni a rabló**tól***: I will defend you from the robber.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The application of vowel harmony gives two different suffixes: *-tól* and *-től*.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] These are applied to back-vowel and front-vowel words, respectively.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] Hungarian has a narrower delative case, similar to ablative, but more specific: movement off/from a surface of something, with suffixes *-ról* and *-ről*.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] In some situations simple ablative can have a "because of" meaning; in these situations, ablative can be optionally followed by the postposition *dolayı* 'because of'.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative in Manchu is expressed through the suffix *-ci* and can also be used to express comparisons.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] It is usually not directly attached to its parent word.
[src:buryat-language/ablative] The ablative in Evenki is expressed with the suffix *-duk*.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In grammar, the **accusative case** (abbreviated **acc**) of a noun is the grammatical case used to receive the direct object of a transitive verb.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In the English language, the only words that occur in the accusative case are pronouns: "me", "him", "her", "us", "whom", and "them".
[src:buryat-language/accusative] For example, the pronoun *she*, as the subject of a clause, is in the nominative case ("She wrote a book"); but if the pronoun is instead the object of the verb, it is in the accusative case and *she* becomes *her* ("Fred greeted her").
[src:buryat-language/accusative] For compound direct objects, it would be, e.g., "Fred invited me and her to the party".
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is used in many languages for the objects of (some or all) prepositions.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] It is usually combined with the nominative case (for example in Latin).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The English term, "accusative", derives from the Latin *accusativus*, which, in turn, is a translation of the Greek αἰτιατική.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The word can also mean "causative", and that might have derived from the Greeks, but the sense of the Roman translation has endured and is used in some other modern languages as the grammatical term for this case, for example in Russian (винительный).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Some Balto-Finnic languages, such as Finnish, have two cases for objects, the accusative and the partitive case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In morphosyntactic alignment terms, both do the accusative function, but the accusative object is telic, while the partitive is not.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Modern English almost entirely lacks declension in its nouns; pronouns, however, have an understood case usage, as in *them*, *her*, *him* and *whom*, which merges the accusative and dative functions, and originates in old Germanic dative forms (see Declension in English).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In the sentence *The man sees **the dog***, *the dog* is the direct object of the verb "to see".
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In English, which has mostly lost grammatical cases, the definite article and noun – "the dog" – remain the same noun form without number agreement in the noun either as subject or object, though an artifact of it is in the verb and has number agreement, which changes to "sees".
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In a declined language, the morphology of the article or noun changes with gender agreement.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] For example, in German, "the dog" is *der Hund*.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] This is the form in the nominative case, used for the subject of a sentence.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] If this article/noun pair is used as the object of a verb, it (usually) changes to the accusative case, which entails an article shift in German – *Der Mann sieht **den Hund*** (The man sees the dog).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In German, masculine nouns change their definite article from *der* to *den* in the accusative case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Nepali, "Rama sees Shyama" would be translated as रामले श्यामलाई देख्छ। *Rama-le Shyama-lai dekhchha.* The same sentence in Sanskrit would be रामः पश्यति श्यामम्। *Rama: pashyati Shyamam*.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case in Latin has minor differences from the accusative case in Proto-Indo-European.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] For the accusative endings, see Latin declensions.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is used for the direct object in a sentence.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The masculine forms for German articles, e.g., "the", "a/an", "my", etc., change in the accusative case: they always end in -en.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The feminine, neutral and plural forms do not change.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Some German pronouns also change in the accusative case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is also used after particular German prepositions.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] These include *bis*, *durch*, *für*, *gegen*, *ohne*, *um*, after which the accusative case is always used, and *an*, *auf*, *hinter*, *in*, *neben*, *über*, *unter*, *vor*, *zwischen* which can govern either the accusative or the dative.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The latter prepositions take the accusative when motion or action is specified (being done into/onto the space), but take the dative when location is specified (being done in/on that space).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] These prepositions are also used in conjunction with certain verbs, in which case it is the verb in question which governs whether the accusative or dative should be used.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Adjective endings also change in the accusative case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Another factor that determines the endings of adjectives is whether the adjective is being used after a definite article (the), after an indefinite article (a/an) or without any article before the adjective (*many* green apples).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In German, the accusative case is also used for some adverbial expressions, mostly temporal ones, as in *Diesen Abend bleibe ich daheim* (This evening I'm staying at home), where *diesen Abend* is marked as accusative, although not a direct object.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Russian, accusative is used not only to display the direct object of an action, but also to indicate the destination or goal of motion.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The prepositions в and на can both take accusative in situations where they are indicating the goal of a motion.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In the masculine, Russian also distinguishes between animate and inanimate nouns with regard to the accusative; only the animates carry a marker in this case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The PIE accusative case has nearly eroded in Russian, merging with the genitive or the nominative in most declensions.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Only singular first-declension nouns (ending in 'а', 'я', or 'ия') have a distinct accusative ('у', 'ю', or 'ию').
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Polish, the accusative case has two functions: showing the direct object of an action, and showing the goal of motion.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Inanimate masculine nouns in accusative case are usually written the same as in nominative case, whereas animate masculine nouns receive the ending ***-a***.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Feminine nouns ending with a consonant are written the same as in nominative case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Neuter nouns are written the same in accusative case as they are in nominative case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The direct object function of the accusative case in Polish is often used with verbs like *mieć* 'to have', *jeść* 'to eat', *pić* 'to drink', *czytać* 'to read' and *lubić* 'to like'.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The motion function of the accusative case is used with the prepositions *na*, *o*, *po*, *pod*, *przez(e)*, *w(e)*, and *za*.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] According to the traditional Finnish grammar, the accusative case is used for a total object, while the partitive case is used for a partial object.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative is identical to either the nominative case or the genitive case, except for personal pronouns and the personal interrogative pronoun *kuka*/*ken*, which have a special accusative form ending in *-t*.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The major new Finnish grammar, *Iso suomen kielioppi*, deviates from the traditional classification to limit the accusative case to the special case of personal pronouns and *kuka*/*ken*.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] This grammar considers other total objects as being in the nominative or genitive case.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is assigned to the direct object in a sentence in Hungarian.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative marker is always *-t*, often preceded by a linking vowel to facilitate pronunciation.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Every personal pronoun has an accusative form.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] For the Hungarian 1st and 2nd person singular accusative forms, the pronoun can often be dropped if it is clear from the context who the speaker is referring to.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Accusative case marking existed in Proto-Semitic, Akkadian, and Ugaritic.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] It is preserved today in many Semitic languages as Modern Standard Arabic, Hebrew and Ge'ez.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is called in Arabic النصب (*an-naṣb*) and it has many other uses in addition to marking the object of a verb.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Hebrew, if the object of the sentence is a pronoun (e.g., I, you, s/he) and the transitive verb requires a direct object, the word אֵת *et* is combined with the pronoun into an object pronoun.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Japanese, cases are marked by placing particles after nouns.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is marked with を (*wo*, pronounced /o̞/).
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Korean, the accusative case is marked with 를 or 을.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The postpositions depend on a word's last syllable.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Turkish, cases are marked with suffixes.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative case is marked with the suffixes *-ı, -i, -u, -ü*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] If a word ends in a vowel, *-y-* is added before the suffix as a buffer consonant.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The accusative is only used if the direct object of a sentence is definite.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] If it is indefinite, the nominative case is used.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] In Malayalam, the accusative inflection is achieved using the suffix എ /-e/.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] The sandhi also play a role here depending on the ending of the noun.
[src:buryat-language/accusative] Example: മരം /maram/ → മരത്തെ /maratte/ where /tt/ replaces /m/ when /e/ is suffixed.
[src:buryat-language/achang-language] The **Achang language** (Achang: **Ngachang**; Chinese: 阿昌, Burmese: အာချန်) is a Tibeto-Burman language spoken by the Achang (also known as Maingtha and Ngochang) in Yunnan, China, and northern Myanmar.
[src:buryat-language/achang-language] The Xiandao dialect (100 speakers; autonym: *Chintaw* /kʰan³¹tau³¹/) is spoken in the following two locations in Yingjiang County, Dehong Prefecture (*Xiandaoyu Yanjiu*).
[src:buryat-language/achang-language] Voiced sounds /b, d, dz, dʒ, ɟ, ɡ/ can also be heard as voiceless [p, t, ts, tʃ, c, k] in free variation among speakers.
[src:buryat-language/achang-language] /i, ɛ, aˑ/ can also have lax vowel counterparts as [ɪ, æ, ʔaˑ].
[src:buryat-language/achang-language] Achang word order is subject–object–verb.
[src:buryat-language/achang-language] There is no dominant order for nouns and their adjective modifiers.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe is closely related to the Kabardian or East Circassian language; some reject the distinction between the two languages in favour of both being dialects of a unitary Circassian language, others argue they are closely related but technically distinct languages.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Despite phonological differences, Circassian languages are reciprocally intelligible, with speakers being able to communicate with varying degrees of efficiency.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] While the self-designation for both Adyghe and Kabardian language is *Adyghe*, in linguistic and administrative terms, "Adyghe" refers specifically to the language of the western tribes of Circassians, while "Kabardian" refers to the language of the two eastern tribes (Kabardians and Besleney).
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Ubykh, Abkhaz and Abaza are more distantly related to Adyghe.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe is also known as West Circassian or Lower Circassian.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe belongs to the Northwest Caucasian language family.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Glottochronological studies suggest that the common Proto-Northwest Caucasian language split into the Circassian, Abkhaz, and Ubykh branches roughly 5,000 years ago.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] One of the earliest attempts to create a standard for the Adyghe language was made by Natouko Sheretluk (Natouko Efendi), a Shapsug nobleman.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] He opened a madrasa in his native village of Bogundyr and compiled an Adyghe alphabet and grammar.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Leonty Lyulye, a Russian official who lived for many years among the Shapsugs, Natukhays, and Abadzekhs on the Black Sea coast, published a "Russian-Circassian Dictionary" and a brief grammar in Odessa in 1846.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Lyulye identified three dialects of Adyghe: "Kabardian", "Besleney", and a third he called "Common Circassian" (referring to the Western coastal dialects).
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] He tried to base his dictionary on this "Common" dialect.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Another pre-Soviet attempt was made by Wumar Bersey, an Abzakh.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] On March 14, 1853, he published the "Primer of the Circassian Language" (Adyghe Alphabet) in Tiflis (Tbilisi), based on the Arabic script.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This date (March 14) is now celebrated annually as the "Day of the Adyghe Language".
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The standard register of Adyghe, known as Literary Adyghe (Adyghe: Литературабз, lit.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] 'Literature language'), was created by Circassian linguist Daut Ashkhamaf based largely on the Chemguy dialect, which was chosen for its simplicity.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] However, Literary Adyghe is a constructed dialect and is distinct from the natural Chemguy dialect, as there was significant input from the dialects of other tribes who remained in the Caucasus after the Circassian exile, spesifically the Bzhedug, Shapsug, and partly Abzakh.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the 1930s, Ashkhamaf even utilized the term "Bzhedug-Temirgoy dialect" to describe the basis of the literary language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] He argued that through the development of the literary language, these dialects were merging.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In some cases, literary dialect preferred words from other dialects over Chemguy words, such as Bzhedug "ӏэ" (hand) and "тхьэ" (god) instead of the Chemguy "ӏа" and "тхьа", as well as specific ordinal numbers and verb forms.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Thus, being supra-dialectal, literary Adyghe stands in contrast to territorial dialects and serves as the unifying literary form of the language for speakers of diverse dialects.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] There were proposals to merge Adyghe and Kabardian to create a single Circassian literary language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Another proposal was to select one of the two to serve as the single literary language for all Circassians.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] A rejected proposal by Circassian scholars argued for recognizing Kabardian as the sole literary language for all Circassians, as it had the most speakers.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] There were attempts to create a single unified alphabet for Adyghe, Kabardian, Chechen and Karachay-Balkar; but efforts failed because the leaders of the movement were accused of being "bourgeois nationalists" and executed in 1937.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Naloev, who was involved in the creation of the Kabardian alphabet, was executed by firing squad for alleged treason; he was rehabilitated posthumously in 1957.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Bolsheviks supported the creation of separate alphabets and grammars for the "Kyakh" (Western; the modern Adyghe language) and Kabardian, despite ongoing debates on unifying them.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Thus, Adyghe and Kabardian speakers could communicate easier orally as opposed to in writing due to different graphical representations and spelling rules.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] A more moderate proposal developed by the linguist M.A.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Kumakhov aimed to unify the alphabets and orthography without forcing a complete merger of spoken Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This project proposed standardizing the representation of identical phonemes (using the same letter for the same sound where they currently differ, such as the Adyghe `жъ`vs.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The project was accepted by specialists at regional conferences in Nalchik and Maikop in 1998 and 1999.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] While the Parliament of the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic approved the project, the Parliament of the Republic of Adygea did not proceed to discuss it.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Cherkess) was a result of Soviet "ethnic engineering".
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The International Circassian Association (ICA) officially stated the goal of creating a "uniform Circassian language" in its 2015 congress resolution.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] There are many books written in or translated into Adyghe. А significant milestone was the publication of the "ABC-book of the Circassian language" by Wumar Bersey in Tbilisi on March 14, 1853, a date now celebrated as the Day of the Adyghe Language and Writing.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the early 20th century, reformist movements in Baksan led to the publication of religious and ethical textbooks such as "The History of Islam" (Мыслъымэн Тхыдэ) in 1918.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] A popular Adyghe translation of the Quran was made by Koshbaye Pshimaf Iskhak Mashbash.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The New Testament and many books of the Old Testament have been published in Adyghe by the Institute for Bible Translation in Moscow.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 2020 a bilingual edition of Ecclesiastes was released in Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 1908, Circassian Union and Charity Society in Istanbul began printing Adyghe language texts in the newspaper *Ghuaze.* Following this, the "*Adığe-Gazete"* (Adyghe Newspaper) was introduced in 1919.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 1920, the bulletin "Diyane" was published in Istanbul using a Latin-based Adyghe alphabet.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the Middle East, a Circassian cultural society established in 1927 in El-Quneitra, Syria, published the newspaper "Mardzh" (Voice) from 1928 to 1932.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe Maq is the main Adyghe language newspaper in Russia.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] It is published in the capital of the Adyghe Republic, Maykop, five times a week.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The newspaper *"*Socialist Adygea" started in Krasnodar in 1926 and relocated to Maikop ten years later. he Adigean branch of the Union of Soviet Writers launched the literary almanac "Friendship" in Maikop in 1946.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] For younger readers, the children's magazine *"*Constellation" is published in the Adyghe language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Other early newspapers included *Qerehetlıq* (Black People) in 1924 and *Adığe Psevuç* (Adyghe Life) in 1926.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] According to the UNESCO 2009 map entitled "UNESCO Map of the World's Languages in Danger", the status of the Adyghe language in 2009, along with all its dialects (Adyghe, Western Circassian tribes; and Kabard-Cherkess, Eastern Circassian tribes), is classified as vulnerable.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe exhibits between 50 and 60 consonants depending on the dialect.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] All dialects possess a contrast between plain and labialized glottal stops.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] A very unusual minimal contrast, and possibly unique to the Abzakh dialect of Adyghe, is a three-way contrast between plain, labialized and palatalized glottal stops (although a palatalized glottal stop is also found in Hausa and a labialized one in Tlingit).
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Shapsug (Black Sea) dialect of Adyghe contains a very uncommon sound: a voiceless bidental fricative [h̪͆], which corresponds to the voiceless velar fricative [x] found in other varieties of Adyghe.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This sound is only known to be used in the Black Sea dialect.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the Black Sea coast Adyghe dialects (e.g.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Shapsug dialect and Natukhai dialect) there exist a palatalized voiced velar stop [ɡʲ], a palatalized voiceless velar stop [kʲ] and a palatalized velar ejective [kʲʼ] that were merged with [d͡ʒ], [t͡ʃ] and [t͡ʃʼ] in most Adyghe dialects.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] For example the Shapsug words "гьанэ" [ɡʲaːna] "shirt", "кьэт" [kʲat] "chicken" and "кӏьапсэ" [kʲʼaːpsa] "rope" are pronounced in other dialects as "джанэ" [d͡ʒaːna], "чэт" [t͡ʃat] and кӏапсэ [t͡ʃʼaːpsa].
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In contrast to its large inventory of consonants, Adyghe has only three phonemic vowels in a vertical vowel system.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Adyghe alphabet contains some inconsistencies between visual representation and pronunciation which can be a point of confusion for learners.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] It is tempting to read the Circassian alphabet letters phonologically, but this is not always accurate.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] These letters are not part of the official alphabet, but they may appear in books that showcase the different dialects.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] For most of its history, Adyghe was an oral language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The folklore, particularly the Nart sagas, served as a repository for the language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Widespread literacy in Adyghe did not exist until the modern era and literacy was limited to a few people.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] From the 6th–5th centuries BC until the first half of the 15th century, the Adyghe people used the Greek alphabet, initially introduced through ancient Greek colonies and later reinforced by the Byzantine Empire and the Christian church.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Early forms of the Cyrillic alphabet were also used during this period due to Russian influence.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] During the 13th to 15th centuries, the development of relations with the Genoese Republic led to some use of the Italian (Latin) script.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the 14th century, along with Islam, the Arabic script was adopted for Adyghe.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] It was referred to as Ajam**,** a writing system for the native language based on the Perso-Arabic script.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Since Adyghe has many more consonants than Arabic, the Ajam system required adding special diacritical marks or inventing new letters to represent sounds.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Early attempts to write Adyghe in modern Cyrillic started as early as 1829 and were followed by similar attempts.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 1853, the Adyghe educator Umar Bersey published the first "Primer of the Circassian Language" based on the Arabic script.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Over the following decades, several authors attempted to further improve the Adyghe Arabic orthography.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The most successful attempt was the alphabet created by Akhmetov Bekukh.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In this version, letters were designated for vowel sounds, and the orthography was transformed from an "Impure abjads to a true alphabet.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 1918, on the initiative of the Kuban Revolutionary Committee, a primer was published in Yekaterinodar.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This official endorsement resulted in a literary boom in Adyghe and the publication of various newspapers, textbooks and other literature, including the *Adyghe Maq*, the main Adyghe language newspaper established in 1923.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] During the abovementioned decades, parallel with this process, the Perso-Arabic orthography had also been standardized for the sister Circassian language of Kabardian.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Although very similar in many aspects, there were minor variations, in which letters were included based on each respective phonology, and there were minor differences in presentation of a few consonants as well.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Arabic script was used until 1927, when as a part of the Soviet "Latinisation" campaign, a Latin-based alphabet was adopted.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Yakovlev and the Adyghe scholar Daud Ashkhamaf.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the late 1930s, the script was converted to Cyrillic to align with Russian.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the diaspora, a new Latin alphabet based on the Turkish alphabet was designed to better facilitate Adyghe and Kabardian education in Turkey, named the ABX alphabet.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe, like all Northwest Caucasian languages, has a basic subject–object–verb typology and is characterised by the ergative construction of sentences.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Turkey hosts the largest Circassian population, but the language lacks any legal recognition.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] However, after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of the modern republic, these schools were banned by the Kemalists.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Following the "Citizen, Speak Turkish!" campaign and the closure of Circassian schools, the language was confined to the home.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In educational settings, speaking Adyghe was strictly banned.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Students faced physical punishment and psychological alienation for speaking Adyghe, including during recess and outside of school grounds.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] To enforce this, teachers formed "discipline committees" made up of student informants.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Publishing in the language also faced state pressure; cultural magazines had to remove Circassian lyrics from traditional songs and publish only the musical notes to avoid government retribution.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Consequently, while the older generation retains fluency, proficiency among those under 50 is significantly diminished.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In a study, Nusret Baş (Бажь Нусрэт), the then-president of the Federation of Circassian Associations, estimated that about 5% of Circassians in Turkey (including people of Circassian descent) speak their native language fluently.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Linguistically, the Adyghe spoken in Turkey exhibits distinct features as it was not subject to the standartisation policies in the Caucasus.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] It contains archaic vocabulary lost in the Caucasus, alongside Turkish loanwords.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] While the Chemguy dialect forms the basis of the literary language in the Republic of Adygea, the majority of the diaspora in Turkey speaks the Abzakh and Shapsug dialects (as well as Kabardian), alongside smaller numbers of Bzhedug and Hatuqay speakers.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Hatuqay dialect is spoken only in Turkey.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In some cases, the physical mixing of different tribes led to dialectal convergence.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Frequent intermarriages between dialect groups led to the use of a mixed Adyghe koine or the dominance of one dialect in multi-tribal areas.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In some cases, the boundaries between dialects became blurred, resulting in a hybrid oral communication style, sometimes even including hybrids with Kabardian or Abaza.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Due to assimilation, Adyghe speakers in Turkey sometimes use Turkish terms for numbers, days of the week, months, and colors.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Significant changes occurred following Turkey's European Union accession process in the early 2000s.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The language policy was liberalized, which prompted revival efforts.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 2012, the Ministry of National Education introduced "Living Languages and Dialects" as an elective course for secondary schools, allowing Adyghe to be taught in public schools.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Classes are only opened if a set minimum number of students apply, and bureaucratic hurdles regarding application windows often hinder access to these classes.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Teachers are subject teachers with basic language skills rather than trained philologists, and they receive limited training in language pedagogy.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Educational materials are imported from Adygea and are designed for native speakers, making them difficult to adapt for diaspora students who are learning Adyghe as a second language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] During the COVID-19 pandemic, transnational online courses were organized in collaboration with institutions in Russia, allowing students in Turkey, Jordan, and Germany to be taught by teachers directly from the Caucasus.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Düzce University has a Department of Caucasian Languages and Cultures, which offers "Circassian Language and Culture" programs, including the teaching of Adyghe in Cyrillic, as the surrounding region is inhabited largely by Shapsug and Abzakh Circassians.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Boğaziçi University began offering elective Adyghe courses in 2013.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] A significant debate persists in the Turkish diaspora regarding orthography of Adyghe.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Federation of Caucasian Associations (KAFFED) adopted the Cyrillic alphabet in 2004 to maintain continuity with the homeland, but other groups advocate for a Latin-based script to facilitate easier learning for Turkish speakers.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This dispute intensified significantly when the Turkish Ministry of Education approved a Latin-based alphabet, called the ABX Latin Alphabet, for elective Circassian language courses in public schools, effectively creating a dual-alphabet system alongside the existing Cyrillic curriculum.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] KAFFED vehemently opposed this decision, arguing that it creates confusion and severs cultural ties with the autonomous republics in the Caucasus.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Demonstrations were at Ministry of Education offices across the country with slogans including "Hands off my alphabet," "We want our mother tongue's alphabet" and "How does Arabic in Latin letters sound?".
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Ubykh people in Turkey, who originally possessed their own distinct language, largely integrated with the Adyghe during their exile and adopted the Adyghe language as their own.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Ubykh language went extinct in 1992; today Ubykh people speak Adyghe or Turkish.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe State University is working to document Adyghe language and folklore in Turkey.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian community in Israel, concentrated in the Circassian towns of Kfar Kama and Rehaniya, is considered to have one of the highest levels of language maintenance in the diaspora.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe serves as the language of daily communication in the home, school, and public spaces.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 1958-1959, Israeli Circassians made contact for the first time with Circassians in the Caucasus and requested literary material in Adyghe, which they received.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In 1976, the Adyghe language was introduced into the official school curriculum.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] It is a compulsory subject from 6th grade onward, and utilizes textbooks based on the literary standard of the Republic of Adygea.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Despite the dominance of the Shapsug dialect in speech, the written language taught in schools utilizes the Cyrillic alphabet and the Chemguy-based literary standard.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Kfar Kama is inhabited by the Shapsug tribe, while Rihaniya is inhabited by the Abzakh tribe.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Israeli variety of Adyghe also contains unique neologisms.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Even in diaspora communities with highly preserved spoken fluency, such as the compact Circassian settlements in Israel, literacy is a significant challenge; one survey showed that while 81.7% of respondents had advanced speaking proficiency, only 12% reported writing proficiency.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In Jordan, the Adyghe language has historically enjoyed a relatively privileged status, though it currently faces significant pressure, as Arabic has become the dominant language for the younger generation, and the Adyghe language is often restricted to symbolic functions or domestic use.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Consequently, Adyghe in Jordan serves more as a folkloric marker of identity than a functional tool for daily communication.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language in Jordan is currently classified as severely endangered due to a rapid disruption in intergenerational transmission.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The decline of the language was triggered by migration, urbanization, and the dispersion of the Circassian population among the Arabic-speaking majority.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] For example, the expansion of Amman in the early 1900s transformed predominantly Circassian farming villages into diverse urban centres inhabited by Arabs, causing Circassians to become a minority in their original settlements.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Today, Arabic has almost entirely ousted Circassian as the primary language of communication within the home.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Surveys indicate that 21% of children use Circassian at home.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Because schools historically used Arabic as the sole medium of instruction, Circassian parents began speaking Arabic at home to ensure their children would not struggle academically.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe is taught in Prince Hamza Ibn Al-Hussein Secondary School, a school for Jordanian Circassians in Jordan's capital city of Amman.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This school, established by Circassians with support from King Hussein of Jordan, is one of the first schools for the Adyghe communities outside Circassia.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] It has around 750 Jordanian Adyghe students, and aims to preserve the Adyghe language and traditions among future generations.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The diaspora in Jordan has produced dictionaries and linguistic works, such as a Circassian-Arabic dictionary published in 1988.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian Charity Association of Jordan also sponsors a school between Naur and Wadi Al-Seer that teaches the language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Historically, various dialects were spoken by immigrants, including Shapsug, Bzhedug, (and Kabardian), but over time these dialects have merged.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Historically, the Golan Heights served as a centre for Circassian language preservation prior to the 1967 war.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the 1920s and 1930s, the "Circassian Society of Education and Union" in Quneitra published the newspaper *Mardj* in Circassian (using the Latin script), Arabic, and French, and established a school that taught the language alongside general subjects.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In the late 20th century, the Circassian Charity Association in Damascus operated informal language circles to teach the Cyrillic script and preserve oral traditions.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] However, the language has declined due to the lack of state-supported education and the dominance of Arabic in all public spheres.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] After the Syrian defeat in the war, the Circassian population largely fled the Golan Heights region, which was occupied by the Israeli Army.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Many of Syria's ethnic Circassians have left the country and have repatriated to Adygea, Kabardino-Balkaria and Karachay-Cherkessia, as well as to partially recognised Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian American community is multilingual, speaking languages including English, Circassian (Adyghe, Kabardian), and Arabic.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] However, the community is currently experiencing a significant language shift away from their ethnic Adyghe language and toward English.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] English is the dominant language used in almost all public and social domains, utilized universally in the workplace and overwhelmingly with neighbors, non-Circassian friends, and even among Circassian peers.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language remains preserved primarily within the home, specifically in intergenerational communication.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Circassian is predominantly spoken by the elder members of the community and is the primary language used when younger generations address their grandparents, representing over 52% of these interactions.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] A study found that a large majority of the New Jersey Circassian community (81.5%) agrees that learning the Circassian language is essential for maintaining their ethnic identity.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] However, some Circassian Americans have abandoned Adyghe fluency as redundant, focusing instead on Adyghe Khabze, traditional dances and folklore.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian Benevolent Association (CBA) hosts a Sunday school where volunteers teach the Circassian language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In recent years, growing political pressure and the criminalization of civil society initiatives in Russia have forced many scholars and language activists to relocate, shifting the epicenter of Circassian language activism and cultural preservation to countries abroad, including the United States.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Following the Circassian Genocide and expulsion in 1864, the majority of Adyghe speakers were scattered across the Ottoman Empire.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The language spoken in the diaspora has diverged from the literary forms in the Caucasus.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Diaspora communities often use Arabic or Turkish loanwords where the literary language uses Russian ones.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The linguistic divergence between the Adyghe language spoken in the historical homeland and the language spoken by the diaspora, particularly in Turkey and the Middle East, is the result of over a century and a half of isolated development.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This isolation, combined with the mixing of various dialects and the strong influence of local languages like Turkish and Arabic, led to significant phonetic, lexical, and semantic differences.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Some native Adyghe words acquired entirely new meanings in the diaspora.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The word *гу*, which historically means "wagon" or "cart" in the literary language, has evolved to mean "automobile" or "car" among diaspora speakers.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Similarly, the word *ин* (big) is used in the diaspora to refer to an "elder," replacing the literary term *нэхъыжь*.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Due to intense influence of the Russian language, Russian loanwords in standart Adyghe are left exactly as is and not adapted to the language in terms of spelling or pronouncation.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Turkish linguistic influence led to the creation of calques (literal translations) for modern concepts.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In some extreme cases, diaspora speakers even attach Turkish grammatical suffixes, such as the past tense *-miş* or the subjunctive *-dı*, directly to Adyghe roots, though native speakers often recognize these constructions as "non-Adyghe".
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] While the spoken and folkloric language of the diaspora evolved independently, this isolation has begun to diminish.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] With the advent of the internet and social media, the younger and middle generations in the diaspora are increasingly interacting with the Cyrillic-based literary language of the homeland.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] This exposure is initiating a slow but inevitable "literaturization" of the diaspora's language, gradually aligning their written and official communication with the literary standard.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] When conversing in Turkish, diaspora Circassians frequently embed native Adyghe terms to refer to specific traditional and unique cultural conventions, or use them as in-group slang.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Besides native vocabulary, the Adyghe language has accepted loanwsome ords from Turkic, Arabic, Persian, Russian and other languages.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] The appearance of Turkic loanwords in the Adyghe language can be dated to the 14th century due to interactions with the Golden Horde and Crimean Khanate.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] By the mid-19th century; Arabic words had begun to enter the language.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] Words such as *chapych* (kopeck) are pre-revolutionary loans from Russian.
[src:buryat-language/adyghe-language] In old borrowings, as a rule, the phonetic composition of borrowed words was adapted to the phonological system of the Adyghe language.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Aghul belongs to the Eastern Samur group of the Lezgic branch of the Northeast Caucasian language family.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Glottolog splits the Aghul language between the Qushan/Koshan group and other Aghul dialects due to the Qushan dialects being unintelligible with the other dialects.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] In 2002, Aghul was spoken by 28,300 people in Russia, mainly in Southern Dagestan, as well as 32 people in Azerbaijan.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] There are nine languages in the Lezgian language family, namely: Aghul, Tabasaran, Rutul, Lezgian, Tsakhur, Budukh, Kryts, Udi and Archi.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Aghul has contrastive epiglottal consonants.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Aghul makes, like many Northeast Caucasian languages, a distinction between tense consonants with concomitant length and weak consonants.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] The tense consonants are characterized by the intensiveness (tension) of articulation, which naturally leads to a lengthening of the consonant, so they are traditionally transcribed with the length diacritic.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] The gemination of the consonant itself does not create its tension, but morphologically tense consonants often derive from adjoining two single weak consonants.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Some Aghul dialects have a large number of permitted initial tense consonants.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] The Aghul alphabet was devised in the 1990s.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Ever since then, it has been used as a language of education, with primers, textbooks, and dictionaries published.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] There are four core cases: absolutive, ergative, genitive, and dative, as well as a large series of location cases.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] All cases other than the absolutive (which is unmarked) and ergative take the ergative suffix before their own suffix.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Independent and predicative adjectives take number marker and class marker; also, case if used as nominal.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Thus *idžed* "good", ergative, *idžedi*, etc.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] *idžedar*; but *Idže insandi hhuč qini* "The good man killed the wolf" (subject in ergative case).
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Іисайи пуная гебурис: – ДуьгІе акье миштти: «Дад, Ве ттур гирами хьурай; Ве Паччагьвел адирай. ТІалаб аркьая чин Вакес гьер ягьас гуни. Гъил гьушен че гунагьарилас, чинна гьил гьуршанду кІилди час Іайвелар аркьаттарилас. ХІа темехІера хьас амарта час».
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] ˡisaji punaja geburis: – Du’gˡe ak’e mištti: "Dad, Ve ttur girami x’uraj; Ve Paččag’vel adiraj.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Tˡalab ark’aja čin Vakes g’er jag’as guni.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] G″il g’ušen če gunag’arilas, činna g’il g’uršandu kˡildi čas ˡajvelar ark’attarilas.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] And he said unto them, When ye pray, say, Our Father which art in heaven, Hallowed be thy name.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] Thy will be done, as in heaven, so in earth.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] And forgive us our sins; for we also forgive every one that is indebted to us.
[src:buryat-language/aghul-language] And lead us not into temptation; but deliver us from evil.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The majority of Buryat speakers live in Russia along the northern border of Mongolia.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In Russia, it is an official language in the Republic of Buryatia and was an official language in the former Ust-Orda Buryatia and Aga Buryatia autonomous okrugs.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In the Russian census of 2002, 353,113 people out of an ethnic population of 445,175 reported speaking Buryat (72.3%).
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Some other 15,694 can also speak Buryat, mostly ethnic Russians.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Buryats in Russia have a separate literary standard, written in a Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] It is based on the Russian alphabet with three additional letters: Ү/ү, Ө/ө and Һ/һ.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] There are at least 100,000 ethnic Buryats in Mongolia and Inner Mongolia, China, as well.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The delimitation of Buryat mostly concerns its relationship to its immediate neighbors, Mongolian proper and Khamnigan.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] While Khamnigan is sometimes regarded as a dialect of Buryat, this is not supported by isoglosses.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The same holds for Tsongol and Sartul dialects, which rather group with Khalkha Mongolian to which they historically belong.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Based on loan vocabulary, a division might be drawn between Russia Buryat, Mongolia Buryat and Inner Mongolian Buryat.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] However, as the influence of Russian is much stronger in the dialects traditionally spoken west of Lake Baikal, a division might rather be drawn between the Khori and Bargut group on the one hand and the other three groups on the other hand.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Buryat has the vowel phonemes /i, ʉ, e, a, u, o, ɔ/ (plus a few diphthongs), and the consonant phonemes /b, g, d, tʰ, m, n, x, l, r/ (each with a corresponding palatalized phoneme) and /s, ʃ, z, ʒ, h, j/.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] These vowels are restricted in their occurrence according to vowel harmony.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The basic syllable structure is (C)V(C) in careful articulation, but word-final CC clusters may occur in more rapid speech if short vowels of non-initial syllables get dropped.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Other lengthened vowel sounds that are written as diphthongs, namely ай (*aj*), ой (*oj*), and үй (*yj*), are heard as [ɛː œː yː].
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Also, эй (*ej*) is also rendered homophonous with ээ (*ee*).
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The digraph уй (*uj*) is read as the diphthong [u̟ɪ].
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In unstressed syllables, /a/ and /ɔ/ become [ɐ], while unstressed /ɤ/ becomes [ə].
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Voiced plosives are half-voiced syllable finally on the first syllable (*xob* [xɔb̥] 'calumny', *xobto* [xɔb̥tʰɐ] 'chest'), but completely devoiced on the second syllable onwards (*tyleb* [tʰʉləp] 'shape', *harapša* [harɐpʃɐ] 'shed').
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Velar stops are "postvelarized" in words containing back vowel harmony: ***g**ar* [ɢar̥] 'hand', *xo**g*** [xɔɢ̥] 'trash', but not as in ***g**er* [gɤr̥] 'house', *tee**g*** [tʰeːg̊] 'cross-beam'.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Also, /g/ becomes [ʁ] between back vowels (*jaa**g**aab* [jaːʁaːp] 'what has happened?').
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Lexical stress (word accent) falls on the last heavy nonfinal syllable when one exists.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Otherwise, it falls on the word-final heavy syllable when one exists.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] If there are no heavy syllables, then the initial syllable is stressed.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Secondary stress may also occur on word-initial light syllables without primary stress, but further research is required.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The stress pattern is the same as in Khalkha Mongolian.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Buryat has been a literary language since the 17th century.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Buryats have changed the literary base of their written language three times in order to approach the living spoken language, first using the Mongolian script, switching to Latin in 1930, and finally Cyrillic in 1939, which is currently used.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] From the end of the 17th century, Classical Mongolian was used in clerical and religious practice.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The language of the end of the 17th—19th centuries is conventionally referred to as the Old Buryat literary and written language.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Before the October Revolution, clerical records of the Western Buryats were made mainly in the Russian language, and not by the Buryats themselves, but by representatives of the tsarist administration, the so-called clerks.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The old Mongolian script was used only by ancestral nobility, lamas and traders Relations with Tuva, Outer and Inner Mongolia.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In 1905, on the basis of the Old Mongolian script, Agvan Dorzhiev developed a script known as *Vagindra*, which by 1910 had at least a dozen books printed.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] However, use of vagindra was not widespread.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In 1926, an organized scientific development of the Buryat Latinized writing began in the USSR.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In 1929, the draft Buryat alphabet was created.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] It contained the following letters: **A a, B b, C c, Ç ç, D d, E e, Ә ә, Ɔ ɔ, G g, I i, J j, K k, L l, M m, N n, O o, P p, R r, S s, Ş ş, T t, U u, Y y, Z z, Ƶ ƶ, H h, F f, V v**.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In February 1930, a new version of the Latinized alphabet was approved.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] It contained letters of the standard Latin alphabet (except for **h, q, x**), digraphs **ch, sh, zh**, and also the letter **ө**.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] But in January 1931, its modified version was officially adopted, unified with other alphabets of peoples within the USSR.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In 1939, the Latinized alphabet was replaced by Cyrillic with the addition of three special letters (**Ү ү, Ө ө, Һ һ**).
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Finally, in 1936, the Khorinsky oriental dialect, close and accessible to most native speakers, was chosen as the basis of the literary language at the linguistic conference in Ulan-Ude.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Buryat is an SOV language that makes exclusive use of postpositions.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Buryat is equipped with eight grammatical cases: nominative, accusative, genitive, instrumental, ablative, comitative, dative-locative and a particular oblique form of the stem.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In September 1931, a joint plenum of the Central Committee and the Central Control Commission of the CPSU (B) was held, which, in line with the decisions of the Central Committee, formulated a course for the construction of a socialist in content and national in form culture of the Buryat people.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In the activities of the Institute of Culture, they saw a distortion of the party line in the development of the main issues of national and cultural construction and gave basic guidelines for the Institute's further work.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The Institute of Culture was tasked with compiling a new literary language based on the East Buryat (primarily Selenga) dialect.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In the early 1930s, the internationalization of the Buryat language and the active introduction of Russian-language revolutionary Marxist terms into it began.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] During the next reform in 1936, there was a reorientation to the Khorin dialect, which is spoken by the largest ethnic subgroup of Buryats.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] A contributing factor to the decision might have been an intention to isolate the Buryats from the rest of the Mongol world.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In 1939, the Buryat language began to be written with the Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The period coincided with active repression of the Buryat intelligentsia, including scholars and statesmen who had been involved in the language reform.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Among them were publicist and literary critic Dampilon, one of the leaders of the Buryat-Mongolian Writers' Union Solbone Tuya, editor of the Buriaad-Mongaliin ynen newspaper B.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Since 1938, Russian was introduced as a compulsory language from the 1st grade, thus consolidating Buryat-Russian bilingualism.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The spelling, alphabet and literary norms on which the language is based were changed.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In the 1940s, the Soviet Union completely stopped printing in the Old Mongolian script.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The so-called "Pan-Mongolian" words, which were actually Mongolian and Tibetan, were massively replaced.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The Buryats are the indigenous people of the Republic of Buryatia, yet today the majority of the republic's residents are of Russian nationality.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] According to the 1989 All-Union Population Census, the region was home to about 1,038,000 people, including 726,200 Russians (70%) and 249,500 Buryats (24%).
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Twenty years later, according to the 2010 All-Russian Census, 461,400 Buryats lived in Russia.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] The permanent population of Buryatia amounted to about 972,000 people, including 630,780 (66.1%) Russians and 286,840 (30%) Buryats.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Since 1937, the territories inhabited by ethnic Buryats are divided between the Republic of Buryatia and the Ust-Ordyn Buryat District in the Irkutsk Oblast, as well as the Aginsky Buryat District in Transbaikal.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] In addition to these administrative-territorial units, Buryats live in some other neighboring districts of the Irkutsk Oblast and Transbaikal.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] One of the reasons for the division of Buryats into different administrative units may have been the fight against so-called pan-Mongolism and Buryat nationalism that began in the 1930s.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] It involved efforts to break the cultural, linguistic, and historical ties of the Buryat-Mongols with Mongolia due to the Stalin regime's fears that the Republic of Buryatia might break away from the USSR and form a common state with other Mongolian peoples instead.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] At the moment, UNESCO has officially included the Buryat language in the Red Book of Endangered Languages.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] According to the 2010 All-Russian Census, 130,500 people in the Republic of Buryatia spoke Buryat, or only 13.4% of the total population.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Currently, the process of reducing the spheres of use of the Buryat language continues.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] Russian is compulsory in Buryat schools, while Buryat is just optional since the early 1970s.
[src:buryat-language/buryat-language] There is a dearth of Buryat-language publications, TV channels, periodicals, etc.
